@NODE ENL "Superview, new from version 1.1g onwards"

	Heeyy!, I finally got round to using multiple windows with CanDo!. This feature replaces
the old 'Enlarge' feature that was present in earlier versions. If you wish to enlarge the window
where you view your list of disks, click on 'superview', this will open a much larger list window
which works as follows:

	1) Click on any disk in the list and the contents will be displayed, click again and you
	will be taken back to the point in the list that you were at before your viewed the 
	contents.

	2) Hit the closebutton or 'Close' to return control to the main screen. (The main program
	is inactive whilst superview is on.)"

** Version 2 onwards, concurrent superview window changed back to separate main window, (multiple
   windows were using up too much buffer space).


@ENDNODE
@NODE NEWEY

	If you select this button, you are offered five options...

	@{"ReAllocate deleted records:" LINK RE} 
	@{"Revise Existing Disk Data: " LINK REV} 
	@{"Edit Database Names:       " LINK ED}
	@{"Delete Database entries:   " LINK DEL}
	@{"Clear Database Completely: " LINK CLE}
@ENDNODE

@NODE CLE "Database management/Clear database completely.."


	This option allows you to delete all records held in the current database you are 
	working on and reset the program ready for you to start afresh.
@ENDNODE
@NODE RE "Database management/reallocate deleted records.."	

	This may be used if you wish to scan a disk using a
	number that is no longer allocated to a disk in your collection. If you select
	This option you will be taken to a screen which asks you to establish which
	numbers are no longer allocated. Click on the ~Find Deleted Entries' button and
	a list of all deleted entries will be displayed. You may click on one of your
	'deleted' entry numbers, when you will be taken to the @{"revise" LINK RSD}  screen 
	with that number pre-loaded as the revision number
@ENDNODE
@NODE REV "Database management/Revise existing disk data.."

	This is similar to @{"the reallocate option" LINK RE} except the program
	assumes that you merely wish to 'revise' the database records for a disk which has 
	had it's contents amended in some way
@ENDNODE
@NODE ED "Database management/Edit database names.."

	This function has been included to enable you to edit the 
	volume name which was added to the list, clicking on this button takes you to the 
	edit window where you may change the title as you choose, for example you may do 
	a lot of DTP and have many fonts disks, if you are lazy, like me, you may find that 
	all of your fonts disks are called 'EMPTY', you may change the title empty to 
	something more meaningful like 'Fonts Small' or 'Fonts Bitmap'. The edits only take 
	place in thelist, the actual DISK volume name is NOT altered.
@ENDNODE
@NODE DEL "Database management/Delete database entries.."


	This function allows you to delete a record on your list 
	which you no longer wish to have, perhaps for a disk which you have re-used. Click 
	on the button and you will be taken to the Delete window where this may be carried 
	out by:

	a) Clicking on the record you wisk to delete
	b) Clicking on the "Delete Now" button

	A requester will pop up asking if you are sure, click yes to continue with the delete 
	or no to cancel.

	After having deleted an entry, you will find that the number that was allocated to the 
	'deleted' entry is no longer allocated, (obviously?). If you wish to reallocate this 
	number to a new disk then you can do this using option 1, above
@ENDNODE
@NODE ATT "Attaching 'comments' to records in the database"


	TurboCAT-Pro now offers you the facility of attaching a comment to a record
in the database. This may be used to keep notes on details of the disk and the
comment stored may be found by using either the 'browser' or by directly typing
in a string similar to the comment that you are looking for.
@ENDNODE
@NODE STATS "Disk Statistics"

	If you wish to find how much free space is left on a disk click on the
'Stats' button where you will be presented with details for that particular
disk. As with the comments section you can freely browse through the Database.
	A note of the total number of scanned disks within the database may also be 
found on this window.
@ENDNODE
@NODE ZZ "Sleep Mode"

	If you wish to keep TurboCAT-PRO running but do not wish to have the main
window open, then click on the 'ZzZzZz' button to shrink the window and free
some memory.

@ENDNODE
@NODE RSD "Re-scanning disks already on the database"


	This screen may be used to re-log a disk which is already in the database,
	for example, you may have altered the disks' contents and wish to
	make a fresh record of what changes you have made. This function may
	also be used where you have deleted a record and wish to re-allocate
	the 'deleted' entries' number.
@ENDNODE

@NODE STAT "What the status bar tells you"

	The Status Bar

	The status bar provides you with information telling you the progress of your work, when 
the progam is idle it flashes "Ready & Waiting..." or if scanning has been paused it flashes 
"Automatic Scanning Paused". Whilst the program is reading data from the disk it will tell you 
that it is Working" and a message indicating progress may be displayed. 

	The central  progress bar will indicate how far through the process it has got. 

@ENDNODE
@NODE SER "How to search for files in the database"

	The 'Search...' Button.

	From Version 3.0c and upwards of TurboCAT the search facility was completely revised. These
revisions have been carried over to TurboCAT-Pro.
When you click on the 'Search...' button you will be taken to a new window which contains two 
viewers and one user field. The idea is that you type into the field the name of the file that you 
are looking for and the program will then examine the database for matches to your search string. 
If any items are matched they will be listed in the top viewer, where if you wish you may 
double-click on any of the 'found' matches to produce a complete list of the contents for that 
disk in the lower viewer.

	The search algorithm is fully recursive and should catch all matches in the database,
if you wish you can make the search case sensitive by clicking the 'Ignore Case' button off.
	I have spent quite a bit of time on this and am pleased with the reults, if you have 
any suggestions then please @{" Write " LINK CORR} and let me know.

				@{" ** Printer Support ** " LINK PRINT}
@ENDNODE

@NODE LOG2 "Switching scanning on and off"

	Scanning ON/OFF

	This is the large button at the centre of the window, as you may have guessed, you 
use this button to 'activate' or 'de-activate' the scanning mode. When selected, the button looks 
selected . This means that whenever a disk is inserted into drive DF0: it will be examined by 
Turbocat-pro and added to your list. One or two things can happen when a disk is examined by turbocat:

	1) If the disk is a NDOS, unformatted or otherwise unreadable, the program will inform you 
that it was unable to obtain any information from the disk. You are offered the option of adding the 
disk as a title ONLY by inserting your own name for the disk, (Handy for some disks which have a 
custom format)

	2) If the program detects that you already have a disk with a similar volume name logged on 
your list, you will be informed and asked if you wish to add the disk anyway, (I always end up with 
lots of disks called EMPTY,  If you decide to add the new disk anyway, you can, if you wish edit the 
volume name which has been added to the list using the @{"EDIT Button" LINK ED} and change the name 
from EMPTY, (or whatever), to something more meaningful like........"Fonts (small)" or "Backdrops", 
you know what I mean?, This function only changes the record on the list NOT the disks' volume name. 
(Handy for tracing stuff later)

If you are about to scan a million disks, (or some amount that seems like a million), see the section 
which discusses The @{"Warn On       " LINK WARN} Button

	Whenever you go into a different mode ie HELP or SEARCH or EDIT etc the scanning Mode is always
switched off, and has to be reset.

@ENDNODE


@NODE SAV "Saving without exiting the program"

	The SAVE button

	There are three places where your work can be saved:

	1) Using the 'Save' button on the main screen will save your work while returning you
	to the main screen to continue work on the current database.

	2) Using the 'Save and switch database' button will save your work to the current database
	and pass you to the database selection screen, ready for you to either quit or select
	a new database.

	3) Using the 'Quit' button on the main screen will offer you the option of saving your work 
	before the program exits.

	You should note that the quit option on the 'database selection' screen does not offer
a save option, this is because at this point no database is loaded.


@ENDNODE
@NODE HELP "On-Line Amigaguide help"

	The Help Button

	There is now an Amigaguide on-line help facility in the program. To use Help, select from the 
	menu, and this amigaguide document will appear. To finish, just close the amigaguide window
	as normal 

@ENDNODE

