@ENDNODE

@NODE WARN "The 'Warn On' Button"

	(Prefs screen). If you find that you wish to scan a fair number of disks called 'Empty', 
or any seriesof disks with identical volume names, then de-selecting this button will disable 
the routine that checks the database for disks already scanned with duplicate names. In other 
words, the warning requester that you would normally get does not appear and the disk will be 
scanned regardless of whether a similar volume name already exists in the database. (This could 
get rather annoying after a while if you were scanning 50 disks called 'Empty'). Using this 
option does, of course mean that duplicate disks, and I mean duplicate in terms of contents, 
could be scanned with No Warn(ing)!

@ENDNODE
@NODE NEW "An explanation of the Main features of TurboCAT-PRO"


	An explanation of the various buttons and functions of TurboCat.

	A) The @{" Database Screen          " LINK DAT} 
	B) The @{" Main Screen              " LINK LOG}

@ENDNODE
@NODE DAT "The Database Screen"

	This is the first screen you see when the program loads.

	The Database feature is something new that was missing from TurboCAT! which many people
asked for. 
	Basically the program operates in a similar way to previous versions of TurboCAT, except
it is now possible to catagorize your collection using Six Separate Databases. When the program 
first loads the main screen offers you any one of the six database selections, (two on the PD 
version) which when selected will ask you to confirm that you wish to load the database that you
have selected, at this point you can proceed or cancel. pressing 'Yes' will take you into 
Turbocat-Pro proper, with the appropriate database loaded.
 
	If you wish you can label your databases with your own titles, ie 'Utilities'.... or 
'PD games', in fact anything you wish to call them, up to a maximum of 13 characters. Having named 
them, you may save the titles for posterity, which means that the program will reload with these 
names applied, without you having to rename them again.
	
	When you have built up your database, you may find it useful to go straight into the 
'Search' or 'Superview' facility as soon as you have loaded your database. You can opt to do this 
by selecting the appropriate button before selecting your database.

	Should you wish, you can also display this Amigaguide by clicking on the 'Help' button.
@ENDNODE
@NODE SS "The Close Database Options Button"

	This facility takes you to a screen with five options:

	a) @{"Switch Database:             "LINK SD}
	b) @{"Save & Switch Database:      "LINK SSD}
	c) @{"Save & Quit Program:         "LINK SQP}	
	d) @{"Quit Program Without Save:   "LINK QPWS}	
	e) @{"Cancel:                      "LINK CL}

@ENDNODE
@NODE SD "Close Database Options:/ Buttons:/The Switch Database Button"

	Allows you to change from the current database to a different one WITHOUT performing a 
save. A warning is given.
@ENDNODE
@NODE SSD "Close Database Options:/ Buttons:/TheSave and switch Database Button"

	Allows you to change from the current Database to a different one, carrying out a save of 
your work before doing so.
@ENDNODE
@NODE SQP "Close Database Options:/ Buttons:/The Save and Quit Program Button"

	This option allows you to quit Turbocat-Pro, carrying out a save of your work before 
doing so.
@ENDNODE
@NODE QPWS "Close Database Options:/ Buttons:/The Quit program without Save Button"

	This option allows you to quit the program WITHOUT carrying out a save. A warning is 
given.
@ENDNODE
@NODE CL "Close Database Options:/ Buttons:/The Cancel Button"

	Takes you back to the main screen if you change your mind about changing the database.
@ENDNODE
@NODE NEW1 "What's new in this version?"

	Synopsis:

	Initial Screen:

	1)	Option to go to either main screen or search screen after loading database.
	2)	Layout of screen different, (better?)
	3)	The help button now brings up this Amigaguide document instead of a small prompt.

	Main Screen.

	1)	The 'Revise' button hase gone, being replaced by 'Database Management...'
	2)	There is a small real-time-clock on the right hand side of this screen now.
	3)	'Quit' has been replaced with 'Close Database Options'
	4)	 'Superview' replaces 'Enlarge' as a list viewer...A bit better, I think

	Other Enhancements/changes

	1)	The 'Add Comments' feature has been improved to make it more useable
	2)	When the date is logged into the database, the format has been revised.
	3)	A new screen, 'ScanPrefs' has been added.
	4)	A new option has been added which now operates within the 'Database Management
		Options' feature. This allows you to Identify all 'Deleted' entries in the
		Database...Useful if you wish to reallocate the numbers. (Charles' Idea)
	5)	The program no longer records '.info' files, (where they exist), recording and
		storing this information serves little purpose, as when searching for a file
		you do not need to search for the '.info' file, just the name of the file you seek
		will do. Storing data about '.info' files consumes memory and slows the program 
		down.....so I dropped it as was simply inefficient.
	6)	Also from version 2 onwards, TurboCAT-Pro is now LZX and LHA 'aware'. This means
		that if you wish, you can have the program automatically unpack and list the 
		contents of these archives. Many magazines now provide coverdisks packed in this 
		way, and being unable to list the contents of these disks was a flaw in earlier 
		versions.
	7)	One external drive (DF1:) is now supported.
@ENDNODE

@NODE PAL "Scanning Preferences"

	From Version 2 onwards the scanning routines were thoroughly overhauled, taking heed of some
	gentle critisism from various sources, (Stand up David Taylor), the program will now scan up
	to one level below root. Now, because of this, the program would naturally attempt to 
	catalogue all of the 'system' files as well, eg libs, c, s, devs etc.. This screen lets 
	you decide what to catalogue, if your thing is to keep records of all your 'c' files, then
	simply deselect the 'c' checkbox and the program will record the contents of any 'c' 
	drawers you put its' way. The same applies to the other items.

	NEW!!

		Also from version 2 onwards, TurboCAT-Pro is now LZX and LHA 'aware'. This means
	that if you wish, you can have the program automatically unpack and list the contents of
	these archives. Many magazines now provide coverdisks packed in this way, and being unable
	to list the contents of these disks was a flaw in earlier versions.

			          @{"*** Floppy Disk Users NOTE ***" LINK NOTE}

	Using the LZX and LHA options:           

	Firstly, both of the programs LZH and LHA are Copyright programs, and therefore I have been
	unable to inclide them in this distribution. They are both, however, easily obtainable from
	PD Libraries and some Magazine Coverdisks. - Amiga Shopper, etc.

	On the prefs screen you will see the two checkboxes for lha and lzh. Since I have not
	included these programs on this disk, TCP will check your 'c' drawer for 'lha' or 
	'LZX_68000EC'. If it does not find these programs, this feature is automatically disabled.

	

	EXTERNAL DRIVE DF1:

	Also from Version 2, users with a DF1 drive can select it as the scan drive.

	Other features:

	The @{"Warn On       " LINK WARN} Button	

@ENDNODE

@NODE NOTE "Important!"

	To be able to use the 'Unpack LZX or LHA' features your system must have the following:

	a) A hard drive

	
	OR

	b) A second floppy drive.

	Hard drive users need to have the programs LHA and LZX_68000EC in the 'C' Drawer of their
	boot partition.

	Floppy drive users should place copies of LZX_68000EC and LHA into the 'C' Drawer on their
	Boot Disk, this should preferably be the 'TurboCAT-Pro' disk. Your Amiga can then be booted
	from the TurboCAT-Pro disk in drive DF0: and scanning set to operate on DF1:

	The above features simply will not operate properly on a single floppy drive system, sorry!
@ENDNODE
	





